content.description: This crack goes from fingers to off-hands in just 25'.  If only it were longer.  It starts overhanging on fingers up to a mid-point ledge.  It then continues to the top on off-hands terrain.
content.location: On the far left end of the crag.  About 50-60' left of the Key Crack.

climbs.name: Super Key
climbs.fa: W. Smith, E. Gardner, D. Tower 98

content.description:
It got the name as the FA was on Superbowl Sunday, but it's also the best route here. Go up the center of the prominent steep black tooth past two bolts to a two bolt anchor. You might want a piece for between the anchor and the last bolt and a nut low at the start, (it starts over a slot).

If it was twice as long it would deserve 3 stars for sure!
content.protection: Quasi Sport.  2 bolts, 2 bolt anchor, but take a couple of med size pieces.

climbs.name: Steeper Than It Looks
climbs.fa: W. Smith, E. Gardner, D. Tower 98

content.description: In the center of an alcove right and down hill about 50 to 100 ft from The Key Knob face is a deceptively low angle appearing crack.  It's behind the deep shadow on the Keys Point photo. To descend, walk left to the lower rappel as mentioned for the Key Hole.
content.protection: Small to Med. spring gear & nuts, big stuff for the belay.  A bolt protects the exit move.

climbs.name: Puss Boy
climbs.fa: Todd Gordon, Tim Pinar, Brett Pinar, others

content.description: On the same face and just to the right of The Key Knob is this 3 bolt face climb.  It passes a surprising move through 3 steep humps and then easy featured rock to the top, fairly crunchy the whole way.
content.protection: 3 bolts for the hard bits and some random gear for the easy bits, medium stoppers or assorted small-medium cams.  Bolted belay/rap anchor.

climbs.name: The Key Knob
climbs.fa: E. Gardner, W. Smith, D. Tower 98

content.description: There's a large knob on the face just to the right of the Super Key tooth.  Solo up to the knob, sling it and continue to the top.  Descend as for The Key Hole.
content.protection: Not Much, a sling for the Knob and some wide pieces for the crack above.

climbs.name: The Key Hole
climbs.fa: W. Smith, E. Gardner, D. Tower, T. Martin, E. Ying 98

content.description: Climb easy rock to the right of the Key Crack, then chimney up through the center of the summit block and pop your head out like a gopher. More of a novelty climb than anything else, but still kind of cool. To descend go down a little to the west and wrap the rope around the pocketed triangular block and rap, (No rap slings required). A second rap can be made from a slung block on the next ledge down, (right of The Key Knob).
content.protection: Only a couple of pieces, nuts, long slings

climbs.name: The Key Crack
climbs.fa: TR, W. Smith, E. Gardner, D. Tower, T. Martin, E. Ying 98

content.description: This climbs the left facing dihedral just right of The Key Hole. Climb the wide jamcrack,(5.9ish) to a platform and then go up the corner. The crux is geting started off of the platform. Descend by either continuing up easy ground to the top and descend as for the Key Hole or walk off left.
content.protection: This one is leadable if someone wants to bring a KB and hammer.  Please leave the pin fixed.

climbs.name: Keeping the Dragon At Bay
climbs.fa: Todd Gordon, Tucker Tech, Brett Pinar, Tim Pinar, Greg Epperson

content.description: Crack to 2 bolt anchor   This climb is right of Steeper than it Looks, and left of Broken Plates.
content.location: Key's Point Area of N. Wonderland

climbs.name: Fage
climbs.fa: FA: (TR)  Tim Pinar, Todd Gordon    FA: (Lead)  Adam Stackhouse

content.description: Climb the face left of Broken Plates.  Start in a short crack  (1" to 1 1/2") then up a face past six bolts to a bolted anchor.
content.protection: A couple of pieces for the crack at the start, then six bolts to a bolted anchor.
content.location: Located just left of Broken Plates

climbs.name: Cherry Glazer
climbs.fa: Brett Pinar, Tucker Tech, Todd Gordon, Brian P., Rhesa Ashbachar

content.description: On the face just to the right of The Key Crack is this short edgy face with three bolts.  Climb easy an easy crack to reach the bolts, the same as Key Crack.  Bolted rap anchor at the top.
content.protection: 3 bolts, maybe a piece for the starting crack...

climbs.name: Cheap Pottery
climbs.fa: W. Smith, E. Gardner, D. Tower, T. Martin, E. Ying E. Rivera 98

content.description:
Climb the crack at the right margin of the Broken Plates face, up, around the corner, and up some more.

The rock at this end of the formation isn't that great.

climbs.name: Broken Plates
climbs.fa: W. Smith, E. Gardner, D. Tower, T. Martin, E. Ying E. Rivera 98

content.description: At the right end of the formation there's a wide face just above a very large Pinion Pine. Set up a TR and wander up whatever doesn't move.  The FA sounded like the end of the meal in a Greek restaurant.
content.protection:
TR

PROTECTION UPDATE 4/2015

7 bolts to a 2 bolt anchor.
